INSERT INTO `diseases` VALUES ('Varicose veins','Varicose veins are swollen, twisted veins that usually appear near the surface of the skin, most commonly in the legs. Varicose veins occur when the valves inside the veins become weak or damaged. Normally, these valves help blood flow upward toward the heart, but when they weaken, blood can pool in the veins, causing them to swell and become varicose. Varicose veins may cause symptoms such as visible twisted veins, swelling in the legs, aching or heaviness in the legs, throbbing or cramping, itching around the veins, and skin discoloration or ulceration in severe cases. Several factors can increase the risk of developing varicose veins, including genetics (family history), age, being female, pregnancy, obesity, prolonged standing or sitting, and certain medical conditions that increase pressure in the abdomen or pelvis. Diagnosis of varicose veins usually involves a physical examination by a healthcare provider. In some cases, additional tests such as duplex ultrasound may be performed to assess the blood flow in the veins and identify any underlying venous insufficiency. Treatment options for varicose veins depend on the severity of symptoms and may include lifestyle changes, compression stockings, sclerotherapy (injection of a solution to close the vein), laser therapy, radiofrequency ablation, vein stripping, or minimally invasive procedures such as endovenous laser ablation or ambulatory phlebectomy. Although varicose veins are usually not a serious medical condition, they can cause discomfort and may lead to complications such as chronic venous insufficiency, skin ulcers, bleeding from the veins, or superficial thrombophlebitis (inflammation of a blood clot in a vein).','Maintain a Healthy Weight: Aim to maintain a healthy weight through a balanced diet and regular exercise. Excess weight can increase pressure on the veins and exacerbate varicose vein symptoms. Healthy Diet: Maintain a healthy diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins. Avoid excessive salt intake, as it can contribute to fluid retention and swelling in the legs. Avoid Tight Clothing: Avoid wearing tight clothing, especially around the waist, groin, or legs, as this can restrict blood flow and exacerbate varicose vein symptoms. Avoid Prolonged Standing or Sitting: Take frequent breaks to avoid prolonged periods of standing or sitting, which can contribute to poor circulation and exacerbate varicose vein symptoms. If your job requires prolonged sitting or standing, try to change positions regularly and take short walks to promote blood flow. Stay Hydrated: Drink plenty of water throughout the day to stay hydrated and promote healthy blood circulation. Quit Smoking: If you smoke, consider quitting. Smoking can impair circulation and contribute to the development or worsening of varicose veins.','Vascular Surgeon','02c2508a-766c-47f7-8463-2c7916d87158','2024-03-28 05:40:44','2024-03-28 05:40:44'),('Dengue','Dengue is a mosquito-transmitted virus and the leading cause of arthropod-borne viral disease in the world. It is also known as breakbone fever due to the severity of muscle spasms and joint pain,  The primary vectors of the disease are female mosquitoes of the species Aedes aegypti and Aedes albopictus. The clinical diagnosis of dengue can be challenging as many other illnesses can present similarly early in the disease course. Other considerations should include malaria, influenza, Zika, chikungunya, measles, and yellow fever. Untreated severe dengue fever may have a mortality rate of 10% to 20%. Appropriate supportive care reduces the mortality rate to roughly 1%','There is no specific antiviral treatment for dengue fever. Treatment focuses on managing symptoms and providing supportive care, such as rest, hydration with oral rehydration solutions or intravenous fluids (in severe cases), and pain relievers to reduce fever and discomfort. In severe cases of dengue, hospitalization may be necessary for close monitoring and medical interventions.','PCP','100602d0-debc-4ba8-b031-c803c4661984','2024-03-28 05:40:39','2024-03-28 05:40:39'),('Hyperthyroidism','Hyperthyroidism is a condition where the thyroid gland produces too much thyroid hormone, leading to an overactive metabolism. The thyroid gland, located in the neck, produces hormones that regulate metabolism, energy levels, and other bodily functions. These hormones include thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3), Hyperthyroidism occurs when the thyroid gland becomes overactive and produces an excessive amount of thyroid hormones. This can result from various causes, such as Graves\' disease (an autoimmune disorder), thyroid nodules, thyroiditis (inflammation of the thyroid gland), or excessive iodine intake. Symptoms of hyperthyroidism can vary but may include weight loss, increased appetite, rapid heartbeat (palpitations), tremors, sweating, heat intolerance, nervousness, irritability, fatigue, muscle weakness, frequent bowel movements, insomnia, and changes in menstrual patterns. Hyperthyroidism is diagnosed through blood tests that measure levels of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4) and thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). In hyperthyroidism, T3 and T4 levels are elevated, while TSH levels are typically low. Additional tests, such as thyroid imaging or radioactive iodine uptake scans, may be performed to identify the underlying cause of hyperthyroidism. Untreated or poorly managed hyperthyroidism can lead to complications such as heart problems (including atrial fibrillation and heart failure), osteoporosis (weak and brittle bones), eye problems (such as Graves\' ophthalmopathy), and thyroid storm (a life-threatening complication characterized by severe symptoms).','Manage Stress: Stress can exacerbate symptoms of hyperthyroidism, so practice stress-reduction techniques such as deep breathing exercises, meditation, yoga, or mindfulness to promote relaxation and well-being. Maintain a Healthy Diet: Follow a balanced and nutritious diet to support overall health and well-being. Choose foods rich in vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants, and limit processed foods, sugary snacks, and caffeine, which can worsen symptoms of hyperthyroidism. Manage Stress: Stress can exacerbate symptoms of hyperthyroidism, so practice stress-reduction techniques such as deep breathing exercises, meditation, yoga, or mindfulness to promote relaxation and well-being. Follow Treatment Plan: Adhere to the treatment plan prescribed by your healthcare provider, which may include medications, radioactive iodine therapy, or thyroid surgery. Take medications as directed, attend follow-up appointments, and communicate any concerns or changes in symptoms to your healthcare provider. Avoid Triggers: Identify and avoid triggers that can exacerbate hyperthyroid symptoms, such as stress, heat, and certain medications. Be mindful of factors that can worsen symptoms and take steps to minimize exposure when possible.','Endocrinologist','178ce42a-3d7b-4274-8999-7ba70d832176','2024-03-28 05:40:41','2024-03-28 05:40:41'),('Fungal infection','Fungal infections are caused by fungi, which are microorganisms that can invade various parts of the body, including the skin, nails, hair, mouth, throat, and genital area. Fungal infections can affect different areas of the body and are classified based on their location. Common types of fungal infections include athlete\'s foot (tinea pedis), ringworm (tinea corporis), jock itch (tinea cruris), nail fungus (onychomycosis), oral thrush (oral candidiasis), vaginal yeast infections (vulvovaginal candidiasis), and fungal scalp infections (tinea capitis). Symptoms of fungal infections vary depending on the type and location of the infection but may include redness, itching, burning, scaling, cracking, or peeling of the skin, rash, blisters, or discoloration. Infections of the nails or scalp may cause thickened, discolored, or brittle nails or hair loss.','Practice Good Hygiene: Wash your hands regularly with soap and water, especially after using the bathroom, before eating, and after touching surfaces in public places. Keep your skin clean and dry, particularly in areas prone to fungal infections, such as between toes, in skin folds, and under the breasts.  Keep Skin Dry: Moisture creates an ideal environment for fungal growth, so it\'s essential to keep your skin dry, especially in areas prone to sweating. Dry yourself thoroughly after bathing or swimming, and use talcum powder or antifungal powder in areas where moisture accumulates.  Wear Breathable Clothing: Choose loose-fitting, breathable clothing made of natural fibers such as cotton or linen, especially in hot and humid weather. Avoid tight-fitting clothing and synthetic fabrics that trap moisture and heat, promoting fungal growth.  Change Wet or Sweaty Clothing Promptly: If you become sweaty or wet, change out of damp clothing promptly to prevent moisture buildup on the skin. This is particularly important after exercising or engaging in activities that cause sweating.  Protect Your Feet: Wear clean, dry socks made of moisture-wicking materials and change them regularly, especially if your feet tend to sweat. Choose well-ventilated shoes made of breathable materials, and avoid wearing tight or non-breathable footwear for extended periods. Avoid Sharing Personal Items: Do not share personal items such as towels, socks, shoes, or clothing with others, as this can spread fungal infections. Use your towels and personal hygiene items to reduce the risk of contamination.','Dermatologist','1e66541c-ebd3-4054-89b8-5cbc16c0f82a','2024-03-28 05:40:39','2024-03-28 05:40:39'),('hepatitis A','Hepatitis A is a viral infection that primarily affects the liver. Hepatitis A is caused by the hepatitis A virus (HAV), which is typically spread through contaminated food or water or through close contact with an infected person. The virus enters the body through the mouth and travels to the liver, where it causes inflammation. Symptoms of hepatitis A can range from mild to severe and may include fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, loss of appetite, dark urine, clay-colored stools, jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes), and fever. Some people, especially children, may have no symptoms. Hepatitis A is highly contagious and can be spread through close personal contact with an infected person, consumption of contaminated food or water, or by touching surfaces contaminated with the virus and then touching the mouth. Diagnosis of hepatitis A is based on symptoms, medical history, and blood tests that detect antibodies produced by the body in response to the virus. A healthcare provider may order blood tests to confirm the diagnosis and assess liver function. There is no specific treatment for hepatitis A, and the infection typically resolves on its own without causing long-term liver damage. Treatment focuses on relieving symptoms and supporting liver function. Bed rest, adequate hydration, and avoiding alcohol and certain medications that can stress the liver are recommended. While hepatitis A typically resolves on its own, complications such as acute liver failure can occur, especially in older adults and individuals with pre-existing liver disease. Most people recover completely from hepatitis A without long-term liver damage.','Safe Food and Water: Consume safe and clean food and water to reduce the risk of ingesting hepatitis A virus. Avoid consuming raw or undercooked shellfish, fruits, and vegetables that may have been contaminated with fecal matter. Drink bottled water or boiled water, especially in areas with poor sanitation. Practice Good Hygiene: Wash hands thoroughly with soap and water after using the restroom, before handling food, and after changing diapers. Proper hand hygiene can help prevent the spread of hepatitis A virus, especially in settings where there is close personal contact or potential exposure to contaminated surfaces. Avoid Contaminated Surfaces: Be cautious when touching surfaces or objects that may be contaminated with hepatitis A virus, such as bathroom fixtures, door handles, or food preparation surfaces. Clean and disinfect frequently touched surfaces regularly, especially in shared spaces or public settings. Vaccination: The hepatitis A vaccine is highly effective at preventing infection and is recommended for all children, travelers to areas with high rates of hepatitis A, individuals at increased risk of exposure to the virus, and certain high-risk populations. Complete the vaccine series as recommended by healthcare providers.','Gastroenterologist','1f2142f3-80ab-4e93-a3cf-05f52ab14216','2024-03-28 05:40:44','2024-03-28 05:40:44'),('Hypertension ','Hypertension, commonly known as high blood pressure, is a condition where the force of blood against the walls of the arteries is consistently too high. Blood pressure is the force exerted by the blood against the walls of the arteries as it circulates through the body. It is measured using two numbers: systolic pressure (the pressure when the heart beats) over diastolic pressure (the pressure when the heart is at rest between beats). A normal blood pressure reading is typically around 120/80 mmHg.  Hypertension can have various causes, including genetics, lifestyle factors, and underlying health conditions. Risk factors for developing high blood pressure include obesity, lack of physical activity, unhealthy diet (high in salt and processed foods), excessive alcohol consumption, smoking, stress, older age, family history of hypertension, and certain medical conditions such as diabetes, kidney disease, and sleep apnea. Hypertension is often called the \"silent killer\" because it typically doesn\'t cause noticeable symptoms in the early stages. Many people with high blood pressure may not be aware of their condition until they experience a health crisis such as a heart attack or stroke. Regular blood pressure monitoring is essential for early detection and management. If left untreated or poorly managed, hypertension can lead to serious health complications, including heart disease, heart attack, stroke, kidney disease, vision loss, peripheral artery disease, and other problems. It is essential to manage high blood pressure effectively to reduce the risk of complications and improve overall health and quality of life.','Follow a Healthy Diet: Adopt a heart-healthy diet, such as the Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension (DASH) diet, which emphasizes fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and low-fat dairy products while limiting saturated fats, cholesterol, and sodium (salt). Reduce your intake of processed foods, fast food, and foods high in salt, sugar, and unhealthy fats. Limit Salt Intake: Reduce sodium intake by avoiding added salt during cooking and at the table, and by choosing low-sodium or sodium-free alternatives when available. Be mindful of hidden sources of sodium in processed foods, canned goods, packaged snacks, and restaurant meals. Maintain a Healthy Weight: Aim for a healthy body weight by following a balanced diet and engaging in regular physical activity. Losing excess weight, particularly around the waistline, can help lower blood pressure and reduce the risk of hypertension-related complications. Limit Alcohol Consumption: Limit alcohol intake to moderate levels, which is generally defined as up to one drink per day for women and up to two drinks per day for men. Excessive alcohol consumption can raise blood pressure and increase the risk of heart disease and stroke. Quit Smoking: If you smoke, quit smoking and avoid exposure to secondhand smoke. Smoking damages blood vessels, increases blood pressure, and raises the risk of heart disease and other health problems. Seek support and resources to quit smoking, such as counseling, nicotine replacement therapy, or prescription medications. Manage Stress: Practice stress-reduction techniques such as deep breathing exercises, meditation, yoga, mindfulness, or other relaxation techniques to help manage stress levels. Chronic stress can contribute to high blood pressure and negatively impact overall health. Monitor Blood Pressure Regularly: Keep track of your blood pressure at home using a home blood pressure monitor or by visiting your healthcare provider regularly for check-ups. Monitoring blood pressure helps to track progress and ensures that it remains within a healthy range.','Cardiologist','2319228b-2707-497d-9684-128c792365de','2024-03-28 05:40:41','2024-03-28 05:40:41'),('Common Cold','The common cold is a viral infection that affects the upper respiratory tract, primarily the nose and throat caused by various viruses, most commonly rhinoviruses. These viruses are highly contagious and can spread from person to person through respiratory droplets when someone with a cold coughs, sneezes, or talks, or by touching surfaces contaminated with the virus. Symptoms of the common cold usually include a runny or stuffy nose, sneezing, sore throat, cough, mild fever, headache, and fatigue. These symptoms typically develop gradually and are usually mild, although they can vary from person to person, and typically lasting for about 7-10 days.','Boost Immunity: Support your immune system by maintaining a healthy lifestyle with regular exercise, a balanced diet rich in fruits and vegetables, adequate sleep, and stress management. Consider taking supplements like vitamin C or zinc, which may help support immune function. Stay Hydrated: Drink plenty of fluids, such as water, herbal tea, or clear broth, to stay hydrated and support your body\'s natural defenses against infections. Clean and Disinfect: Clean and disinfect frequently touched surfaces and objects in your home, workplace, and other shared spaces regularly. Focus on high-touch surfaces such as doorknobs, light switches, countertops, and electronic devices.','PCP','3274f0e0-c1f3-46c9-98c9-47b21a06ae08','2024-03-28 05:40:39','2024-03-28 05:40:39'),('Hepatitis E','Hepatitis E is a viral infection that affects the liver. Hepatitis E is caused by the hepatitis E virus (HEV), which is transmitted through contaminated water or food. It can also be spread through contact with feces from an infected person. Hepatitis E infection is most common in areas with poor sanitation and limited access to clean drinking water, especially in developing countries. Hepatitis E infection typically manifests as an acute illness, meaning it is a short-term illness that occurs within the first few weeks to months after exposure to the virus. Most people with hepatitis E infection recover fully within a few weeks to months without any long-term liver damage. However, in pregnant women, particularly those in the third trimester, hepatitis E infection can be more severe and may lead to complications such as fulminant hepatitis (severe liver failure), which can be life-threatening for both the mother and the baby. Symptoms of hepatitis E infection may include fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, loss of appetite, dark urine, clay-colored stools, and jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes). Some people with hepatitis E infection may have no symptoms or only mild symptoms, while others may experience more severe illness, especially pregnant women and individuals with underlying liver disease. Hepatitis E infection is diagnosed through blood tests that detect the presence of HEV antibodies and HEV RNA (viral load). These tests can confirm the diagnosis of hepatitis E and assess the severity of liver inflammation and damage.','Practice Good Hygiene: Wash hands thoroughly with soap and water, especially before eating, after using the bathroom, and after handling raw meat or animal products. Proper hand hygiene can help prevent the spread of hepatitis E and other infectious diseases. Ensure Safe Water and Food: Drink only clean, safe water from reliable sources, such as bottled water or water that has been boiled or treated with chlorine or iodine tablets. Avoid consuming water or ice from unknown sources, especially in areas where hepatitis E is endemic. Additionally, avoid consuming raw or undercooked shellfish or pork, as these may be sources of hepatitis E virus. Practice Safe Food Handling: Wash fruits and vegetables thoroughly before consumption, and ensure that meat is cooked thoroughly to kill any potential pathogens, including hepatitis E virus. Avoid cross-contamination by using separate cutting boards and utensils for raw and cooked foods. Consider Vaccination (if available): In regions where hepatitis E vaccines are available and recommended, consider vaccination, particularly if you are at increased risk of exposure to the virus due to travel to endemic areas, occupation, or underlying health conditions that may increase the risk of severe disease. Seek Medical Care: If you develop symptoms suggestive of hepatitis E infection, such as fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, jaundice, or dark urine, seek medical care promptly for evaluation and diagnosis. Early detection and management of hepatitis E infection can help prevent complications and facilitate recovery.','Hepatologist','35dd6791-6431-44f4-8672-c6aa0888f04a','2024-03-28 05:40:41','2024-03-28 05:40:41'),('Tuberculosis','Tuberculosis (TB) is a contagious bacterial infection caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. It primarily affects the lungs but can also affect other parts of the body. TB is spread through the air when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or talks, releasing bacteria-containing droplets that are then inhaled by others. Close and prolonged contact with an infected individual increases the risk of transmission. After exposure to the TB bacteria, some individuals develop latent TB infection, where the bacteria remain inactive in the body and do not cause symptoms. Latent TB is not contagious but can progress to active TB disease if the immune system becomes weakened, allowing the bacteria to multiply and cause illness. Symptoms of active TB disease may include coughing (sometimes with blood), chest pain, fatigue, fever, night sweats, weight loss, and loss of appetite. TB can also affect other parts of the body, causing symptoms such as joint pain, swelling, and neurological symptoms if it spreads beyond the lungs. Diagnosis of TB typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, chest X-ray, and laboratory tests such as sputum smear microscopy, culture, and molecular tests (e.g., PCR). A tuberculin skin test (TST) or interferon-gamma release assay (IGRA) can help detect latent TB infection. TB remains a major global health concern, particularly in low- and middle-income countries with limited access to healthcare resources. Efforts to control TB include improving access to diagnostic testing, implementing effective treatment programs, promoting research and development of new TB drugs and vaccines, and addressing social determinants of health that contribute to TB transmission and progression.','Good Respiratory Hygiene: Cover your mouth and nose with a tissue or your elbow when coughing or sneezing to prevent the spread of respiratory droplets containing TB bacteria. Dispose of used tissues properly and wash your hands afterward. Isolation: Individuals diagnosed with active TB disease should be isolated from others until they are no longer contagious. This may involve staying home from work, school, or other social activities until treatment has been initiated and the risk of transmission has been reduced. Vaccination: In areas where TB is prevalent, vaccination with the Bacillus Calmette-Guérin (BCG) vaccine may be recommended, especially for infants and children at high risk of TB exposure. However, the BCG vaccine is not widely used in countries with low TB prevalence due to variable efficacy and concerns about interference with TB diagnostic tests.','Pulmonology','3e2fb83e-8fb9-4b90-a4d2-293e266419ce','2024-03-28 05:40:43','2024-03-28 05:40:43'),('Allergy','An allergy is when your body reacts to something harmless as if it\'s dangerous. Here\'s how it happens:      Immune System: Your body\'s immune system helps protect you from harmful things like germs. Sometimes, it can mistake harmless substances, like certain foods, pollen, or pet dander, as harmful invaders.      Allergic Reaction: When your body encounters these harmless substances, it may overreact, triggering an allergic reaction. This reaction is your body\'s way of trying to get rid of what it thinks is harmful.','PCP','PCP','46fc90ef-e611-4370-ae01-ae59ce6776fe','2024-03-28 05:40:38','2024-03-28 05:40:38'),('Psoriasis','Psoriasis is a chronic autoimmune skin condition that causes rapid skin cell growth, resulting in thick, red, scaly patches on the skin. Psoriasis occurs when the immune system mistakenly attacks healthy skin cells, causing an overproduction of new skin cells. This rapid turnover of skin cells leads to the formation of thick, raised patches known as plaques. The most common symptom of psoriasis is the development of red, raised patches of skin covered with silvery scales. These patches, or plaques, can appear anywhere on the body but are most commonly found on the elbows, knees, scalp, lower back, and nails. Psoriasis can also cause itching, burning, or soreness in affected areas. Certain factors, known as triggers, can exacerbate psoriasis symptoms or cause flare-ups. Common triggers include stress, infections (such as streptococcal throat infections), injury to the skin (such as cuts or sunburn), certain medications (such as beta-blockers or lithium), smoking, and heavy alcohol consumption.  There are several types of psoriasis, including plaque psoriasis (the most common form), guttate psoriasis (small, drop-like lesions), inverse psoriasis (affects skin folds), pustular psoriasis (pus-filled blisters), and erythrodermic psoriasis (widespread redness and shedding of skin). Diagnosis of psoriasis is typically based on a physical examination of the skin and nails, along with a review of medical history and symptoms. In some cases, a skin biopsy may be performed to confirm the diagnosis and rule out other skin conditions. Psoriasis can have a significant impact on physical and emotional well-being, and individuals with psoriasis may be at increased risk of developing other health conditions, such as psoriatic arthritis (a type of inflammatory arthritis), cardiovascular disease, obesity, and depression. Living with psoriasis can be challenging, but support groups, counseling, and educational resources are available to help individuals cope with the condition and connect with others who understand their experiences.','Avoid Triggers: Identify and avoid triggers that exacerbate psoriasis symptoms. Common triggers include stress, infections, injuries to the skin (such as cuts or scrapes), smoking, heavy alcohol consumption, certain medications (such as beta-blockers or lithium), and exposure to cold, dry weather. Maintain a Healthy Lifestyle: Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins to support overall health and immune function. Regular exercise can also help reduce stress, maintain a healthy weight, and improve circulation, which may benefit psoriasis management. Moisturize: Keep your skin well-moisturized to prevent dryness and itching, which can exacerbate psoriasis symptoms. Use emollients or moisturizing creams regularly, especially after bathing or showering, to help lock in moisture and soothe the skin. Protect Your Skin: Protect your skin from injury and irritation by wearing protective clothing, gloves, and sunscreen when outdoors. Avoid prolonged exposure to cold, dry weather, and use humidifiers indoors to help maintain moisture levels in the air. Monitor Your Skin: Pay attention to changes in your skin and track any triggers or factors that seem to worsen your psoriasis symptoms. By staying vigilant and proactive, you can better manage your condition and prevent flare-ups.','Dermatologist','4a72593c-3932-4297-a2de-e2c3aedaed59','2024-03-28 05:40:43','2024-03-28 05:40:43'),('Hepatitis D','Hepatitis D, also known as delta hepatitis, is a viral infection that affects the liver. Hepatitis D is caused by the hepatitis D virus (HDV), which is a defective virus that requires the presence of hepatitis B virus (HBV) to replicate and cause infection. It can occur as either a co-infection with HBV or as a superinfection in individuals already infected with HBV. Hepatitis D is transmitted through contact with infected blood or bodily fluids, similar to hepatitis B. It can be spread through sharing needles or syringes, receiving contaminated blood transfusions or organ transplants, needlestick injuries in healthcare settings, or from mother to baby during childbirth. Hepatitis D infection can manifest as either an acute or chronic illness. Acute hepatitis D may cause symptoms similar to acute hepatitis B, including fatigue, jaundice, abdominal pain, nausea, and dark urine. Chronic hepatitis D infection can lead to long-term liver damage, cirrhosis, liver failure, or liver cancer. Hepatitis D infection is diagnosed through blood tests that detect the presence of HDV antibodies and HDV RNA (viral load). These tests can determine whether the infection is acute or chronic and assess the severity of liver damage. ','Get Vaccinated: Since hepatitis D infection requires the presence of hepatitis B virus (HBV) to cause infection, getting vaccinated against hepatitis B is the most effective way to prevent hepatitis D. Ensure that you and your family members receive the hepatitis B vaccine series, which is typically given as a three-dose series. Vaccination is recommended for all infants at birth and for individuals who are at increased risk of exposure to HBV. Ensure Sterile Medical Procedures: Ensure that medical and dental equipment is properly sterilized, and that healthcare settings follow strict infection control practices to prevent the transmission of hepatitis D and other bloodborne pathogens. If you undergo medical or dental procedures, ensure that sterile equipment is used to reduce the risk of infection. Avoid Sharing Personal Items: Avoid sharing personal items that may come into contact with blood, such as razors, toothbrushes, nail clippers, or personal hygiene items. Hepatitis D virus can survive outside the body for extended periods, so it\'s essential to avoid sharing items that may carry the virus. Consider Hepatitis B Testing: Since hepatitis D infection requires the presence of HBV, individuals at increased risk of hepatitis D, such as individuals with hepatitis B infection or individuals at risk of HBV exposure, should consider hepatitis B testing to identify infection early and access appropriate care and treatment if needed.','Hepatologist','4d89b893-8f08-4352-b8be-1693b67987b9','2024-03-28 05:40:41','2024-03-28 05:40:41'),('Impetigo','Impetigo is a contagious skin infection characterized by red sores or blisters that can ooze and form a yellowish-brown crust.  Impetigo is caused by bacteria, usually Staphylococcus aureus or Streptococcus pyogenes. It often affects children, but adults can get it too, especially if they have weakened immune systems or have come into contact with infected individuals. The primary symptoms of impetigo are red sores or blisters that quickly rupture and ooze fluid. As the fluid dries, it forms a characteristic yellowish-brown crust that resembles honey or brown sugar. The sores are typically itchy and can occur anywhere on the body, but they\'re most common around the nose and mouth. Impetigo is highly contagious and spreads through direct contact with infected skin or through contact with contaminated objects, such as towels, clothing, or toys. Scratching the sores can also spread the infection to other parts of the body. ','Practice good hygiene, such as frequent handwashing with soap and water, especially after touching the affected skin or coming into contact with potentially contaminated objects. Keep the affected areas clean and covered with clean bandages to prevent scratching and minimize the risk of spreading the infection to others. Avoid Close Contact: If you or your child has impetigo, avoid close contact with others until the sores have healed or until at least 24 hours after starting antibiotic treatment to reduce the risk of spreading the infection. Clean and Disinfect: Clean and disinfect objects and surfaces that may come into contact with infected skin, such as towels, bedding, clothing, and toys. Wash these items in hot water with detergent and dry them on the hottest setting to kill bacteria. Avoid Sharing Personal Items: To prevent the spread of impetigo, avoid sharing personal items such as towels, clothing, razors, or toiletries with others, especially if you have an active infection.','Dermatologist','50a26484-075a-4854-9fca-31e9de58d42b','2024-03-28 05:40:42','2024-03-28 05:40:42'),('Hypoglycemia','Hypoglycemia, often referred to as low blood sugar, occurs when blood glucose (blood sugar) levels drop below normal levels. Glucose is the primary source of energy for the body\'s cells, and its levels are tightly regulated by hormones such as insulin and glucagon. Insulin helps lower blood sugar levels by facilitating glucose uptake into cells, while glucagon raises blood sugar levels by stimulating the release of stored glucose from the liver. Hypoglycemia occurs when blood sugar levels fall below the normal range, typically below 70 milligrams per deciliter (mg/dL). This can happen when there is too much insulin in the bloodstream (resulting in excessive glucose uptake by cells), not enough glucose available in the bloodstream (due to inadequate food intake or prolonged fasting), or excessive release of insulin (as in some medical conditions or as a side effect of certain medications). Hypoglycemia can be caused by various factors, including skipping meals or delaying meals, excessive alcohol consumption, increased physical activity without adequate carbohydrate intake, certain medications (such as insulin or oral diabetes medications), hormonal deficiencies, pancreatic disorders, liver disease, or rare genetic conditions affecting glucose metabolism. Symptoms of hypoglycemia can vary but may include shakiness, sweating, palpitations, hunger, weakness, dizziness, confusion, irritability, headache, blurred vision, difficulty concentrating, slurred speech, seizures, or loss of consciousness. Symptoms can occur suddenly and may vary in severity depending on the degree of blood sugar drop. Preventing hypoglycemia involves maintaining blood sugar levels within the target range through regular monitoring, balanced meals and snacks, consistent carbohydrate intake, and medication management (if applicable). Individuals with diabetes should monitor blood sugar levels closely, adhere to their diabetes management plan, and adjust insulin or medication doses as needed under the guidance of a healthcare provider.','Balanced Meals and Snacks: Eat balanced meals and snacks containing a combination of carbohydrates, protein, and healthy fats to help maintain stable blood sugar levels throughout the day. Avoid skipping meals or delaying meals, as this can lead to drops in blood sugar. Consistent Carbohydrate Intake: Consume carbohydrates consistently throughout the day to provide a steady source of energy for your body. Spread your carbohydrate intake evenly across meals and snacks, and avoid large fluctuations in carbohydrate intake. Regular Monitoring: Monitor blood sugar levels regularly, especially if you have diabetes or are at risk for hypoglycemia. Testing your blood sugar as recommended by your healthcare provider can help you identify and address low blood sugar levels promptly. Alcohol Consumption: If you consume alcohol, do so in moderation and be mindful of its effects on blood sugar levels. Alcohol can cause hypoglycemia, especially if consumed on an empty stomach or in combination with diabetes medications. Exercise Safely: If you exercise regularly, monitor your blood sugar levels before, during, and after physical activity. Adjust your carbohydrate intake and/or insulin doses as needed to prevent hypoglycemia during exercise. Be aware that certain ','PCP','517eb0af-3fd9-4507-9bd8-aeb4c254c899','2024-03-28 05:40:41','2024-03-28 05:40:41'),('Gastroenteritis','Gastroenteritis, often referred to as stomach flu or stomach bug, is a common condition characterized by inflammation of the gastrointestinal tract, causing symptoms such as diarrhea, vomiting, abdominal cramps, and nausea. Gastroenteritis is an inflammation of the stomach and intestines, typically caused by viral, bacterial, or parasitic infections. It is commonly referred to as the stomach flu, although it is not caused by the influenza virus. Gastroenteritis is commonly caused by viruses, such as norovirus, rotavirus, adenovirus, or astrovirus. Bacterial causes include species such as Salmonella, Escherichia coli (E. coli), Campylobacter, and Shigella. Parasites such as Giardia or Cryptosporidium can also cause gastroenteritis, typically through contaminated food or water. Symptoms of gastroenteritis typically include diarrhea (loose or watery stools), vomiting, nausea, abdominal cramps or pain, fever, headache, and occasionally muscle aches. Symptoms can range from mild to severe and may vary depending on the cause of the infection.','Practice Good Hand Hygiene: Wash your hands frequently with soap and water, especially after using the bathroom, changing diapers, and before eating or preparing food. Proper handwashing can help remove viruses, bacteria, and parasites that cause gastroenteritis.  Use Hand Sanitizer: When soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer containing at least 60% alcohol. Apply enough sanitizer to cover all surfaces of your hands and rub them together until dry.  Avoid Close Contact with Sick Individuals: Avoid close contact with people who have symptoms of gastroenteritis, such as vomiting or diarrhea. Refrain from sharing utensils, cups, or food with sick individuals to prevent the spread of the infection.  Practice Food Safety: Handle and prepare food safely to prevent contamination. Wash fruits and vegetables thoroughly before eating or cooking them. Cook meats thoroughly to kill harmful bacteria, and avoid consuming undercooked or raw eggs, meats, or seafood.  Drink Safe Water: Consume safe and clean drinking water to prevent waterborne illnesses. If traveling to areas with questionable water quality, drink bottled water or use water purification methods such as boiling or using water purification tablets.','Gastroenterologist','5215da12-10df-4ed1-844d-11229eeb564f','2024-03-28 05:40:40','2024-03-28 05:40:40'),('Osteoarthristis','Osteoarthritis is a common joint disorder that mainly affects the cartilage, the slippery tissue that covers the ends of bones in a joint. Osteoarthritis occurs when the cartilage that cushions the ends of bones in the joints gradually wears down over time. As a result, the bones may rub against each other, leading to pain, stiffness, and loss of joint function. The most common symptoms of osteoarthritis include joint pain, stiffness, tenderness, swelling, and decreased range of motion. These symptoms may worsen over time and can affect any joint in the body, but osteoarthritis most commonly affects the knees, hips, hands, and spine. Several factors can increase the risk of developing osteoarthritis, including age, genetics, obesity, joint injury or trauma, repetitive stress on the joints, and certain medical conditions such as diabetes or gout. Certain lifestyle changes can help manage osteoarthritis symptoms and improve joint health. These may include maintaining a healthy weight, engaging in regular exercise (such as low-impact activities like walking or swimming), protecting joints from injury, using proper body mechanics, and avoiding activities that aggravate joint pain. Some people with osteoarthritis may find relief from alternative therapies such as acupuncture, tai chi, yoga, or dietary supplements like glucosamine and chondroitin sulfate. While these therapies may help reduce symptoms for some individuals, their effectiveness can vary, and it\'s essential to discuss them with a healthcare provider before trying.','Maintain a Healthy Weight: Excess weight can put additional strain on the joints, particularly weight-bearing joints like the knees and hips. Maintaining a healthy weight through a balanced diet and regular exercise can help reduce the stress on the joints and alleviate symptoms of osteoarthritis. Exercise Regularly: Engage in low-impact exercises that strengthen the muscles around the affected joints and improve flexibility and range of motion. Activities such as walking, swimming, cycling, and gentle stretching exercises can help improve joint function and reduce pain associated with osteoarthritis.  Protect the Joints: Avoid activities that put excessive stress on the joints, such as high-impact sports or activities that involve repetitive motion. Use proper body mechanics and joint protection techniques during daily activities to minimize strain on the joints. Manage Stress: Stress can exacerbate symptoms of osteoarthritis and increase pain perception. Practice stress-reduction techniques such as deep breathing, meditation, yoga, or mindfulness to promote relaxation and reduce stress levels. Stay Hydrated: Drink plenty of water throughout the day to keep the joints well lubricated and support overall joint health. Dehydration can exacerbate symptoms of osteoarthritis, so it\'s essential to stay hydrated.','Rheumatologist','5ca5402a-cb30-4171-af79-226dd509789b','2024-03-28 05:40:42','2024-03-28 05:40:42'),('Typhoid','Typhoid fever is a bacterial infection caused by Salmonella enterica serotype Typhi bacteria. Typhoid fever is primarily spread through the ingestion of food or water contaminated with the feces of an infected person. Poor sanitation and hygiene practices, as well as inadequate sewage disposal systems, contribute to the spread of the bacteria. Symptoms of typhoid fever typically develop one to three weeks after exposure to the bacteria and may include sustained high fever, headache, abdominal pain, weakness, fatigue, loss of appetite, and constipation or diarrhea. In severe cases, complications such as intestinal perforation, gastrointestinal bleeding, or systemic infection (septicemia) can occur. Diagnosis of typhoid fever is based on clinical symptoms, medical history, and laboratory tests, including blood cultures, stool cultures, and serological tests to detect antibodies against Salmonella Typhi bacteria. Typhoid fever is treated with antibiotics to kill the bacteria and reduce symptoms. Commonly used antibiotics include fluoroquinolones, cephalosporins, and azithromycin. It\'s essential to complete the full course of antibiotics as prescribed by a healthcare provider to prevent relapse and the development of antibiotic-resistant strains of bacteria. Without prompt and effective treatment, typhoid fever can lead to severe complications, including intestinal perforation, gastrointestinal bleeding, encephalopathy (brain dysfunction), and death. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial for preventing complications and reducing mortality rates associated with typhoid fever.','Good Hygiene Practices: Practice good hygiene habits, such as washing hands thoroughly with soap and water before eating, after using the restroom, and after handling food. Proper handwashing can help prevent the spread of typhoid bacteria. Safe Food and Water: Consume safe and clean food and water to reduce the risk of ingesting typhoid bacteria. Drink bottled or boiled water, avoid consuming raw or undercooked foods (especially meats, seafood, and eggs), and choose foods that are freshly prepared and served hot. Sanitation: Ensure access to clean and sanitary facilities for waste disposal and sewage management. Improving sanitation infrastructure can help prevent the contamination of food and water sources with typhoid bacteria. Avoid Close Contact with Infected Individuals: Limit close contact with individuals diagnosed with typhoid fever, especially during the acute phase of illness when they may be contagious. Take precautions to avoid exposure to respiratory secretions, feces, or contaminated objects. Seek Prompt Medical Attention: If you develop symptoms suggestive of typhoid fever, such as prolonged fever, headache, abdominal pain, or gastrointestinal symptoms, seek medical attention promptly. Early diagnosis and treatment are essential for effective management of typhoid fever and prevention of complications.','Gastroenterologist','61663731-0cb9-48fc-8cbe-a9601a1b1647','2024-03-28 05:40:43','2024-03-28 05:40:43'),('Pneumonia','Pneumonia is an infection that inflames the air sacs in one or both lungs, which may fill with fluid or pus. Pneumonia is usually caused by bacteria, viruses, or fungi that infect the lungs. These germs are commonly found in the environment or may be spread from person to person through respiratory droplets. Symptoms of pneumonia can vary but often include cough, fever, chills, difficulty breathing, chest pain, fatigue, and sometimes coughing up phlegm. In severe cases, pneumonia can lead to complications such as respiratory failure or sepsis. Certain factors can increase the risk of developing pneumonia, including age (young children and older adults are more vulnerable), weakened immune system, chronic medical conditions (such as asthma, COPD, or heart disease), smoking, recent respiratory infections, and exposure to pollutants or toxins. Diagnosis of pneumonia typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and diagnostic tests such as chest X-ray, blood tests, and sputum culture. These tests help confirm the presence of lung infection and identify the causative agent. Complications of pneumonia can include pleural effusion (buildup of fluid between the lungs and chest wall), lung abscess (pus-filled cavity in the lung), sepsis (a life-threatening response to infection), and respiratory failure. Prompt diagnosis and treatment can help reduce the risk of complications.','Practice Good Hand Hygiene: Wash your hands regularly with soap and water, especially before eating, after using the restroom, and after coughing or sneezing. Proper hand hygiene can help reduce the spread of germs that can cause pneumonia. Get Vaccinated: Vaccination is an essential preventive measure against pneumonia. Make sure to stay up-to-date with recommended vaccines, including the influenza (flu) vaccine and pneumococcal vaccine. These vaccines can help protect against common causes of pneumonia. Practice Respiratory Hygiene: Cover your mouth and nose with a tissue or your elbow when coughing or sneezing to prevent the spread of respiratory droplets that can contain infectious germs. Dispose of used tissues properly and wash your hands afterward. Maintain a Healthy Lifestyle: Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins to support overall health and immune function. Stay physically active and get regular exercise to help strengthen your immune system and maintain lung health. Avoid Smoking and Secondhand Smoke: Smoking damages the lungs and weakens the immune system, making individuals more susceptible to respiratory infections like pneumonia. If you smoke, quit smoking, and avoid exposure to secondhand smoke to reduce your risk of pneumonia. Stay Hydrated: Drink plenty of fluids, such as water or herbal tea, to stay hydrated and keep mucous membranes in the respiratory tract moist. Proper hydration can help prevent dryness and irritation in the airways, reducing the risk of respiratory infections like pneumonia.','Pulmonologist','6aca37c0-c492-476b-bda6-37c865a89fb4','2024-03-28 05:40:43','2024-03-28 05:40:43'),('Heart attack','A heart attack, also known as a myocardial infarction (MI), occurs when blood flow to a part of the heart muscle is blocked, causing damage or death to that area of the heart, A heart attack typically occurs when a coronary artery, which supplies oxygen-rich blood to the heart muscle, becomes narrowed or blocked by a buildup of plaque (atherosclerosis). This blockage can be caused by a blood clot (thrombus) forming in a coronary artery or by a rupture of plaque leading to sudden blockage. When blood flow to a part of the heart is obstructed, the affected heart muscle does not receive enough oxygen and nutrients, leading to damage or death of that area of the heart. The extent of damage depends on the size of the blocked artery and how long the blockage persists. Common symptoms of a heart attack may include chest pain or discomfort (which may feel like pressure, squeezing, fullness, or pain), pain or discomfort in the arms, back, neck, jaw, or stomach, shortness of breath, nausea, lightheadedness, or cold sweats. Symptoms can vary from person to person and may differ between men and women. Several factors increase the risk of having a heart attack, including smoking, high blood pressure, high cholesterol, diabetes, obesity, sedentary lifestyle, family history of heart disease, age (risk increases with age), and excessive alcohol consumption. After a heart attack, recovery often involves lifestyle changes (such as quitting smoking, adopting a heart-healthy diet, exercising regularly, and managing stress), medications to prevent future heart events, cardiac rehabilitation programs, and ongoing monitoring and follow-up with healthcare providers.','Healthy Diet: Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. Limit intake of saturated and trans fats, cholesterol, sodium, and added sugars. Choose foods low in cholesterol and avoid processed and fried foods.  Regular Exercise: Engage in regular physical activity most days of the week. Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic exercise or 75 minutes of vigorous-intensity exercise per week, along with muscle-strengthening activities on two or more days per week. Consult with a healthcare provider before starting a new exercise program, especially if you have existing health conditions.  Maintain a Healthy Weight: Strive to maintain a healthy weight by balancing calorie intake with physical activity. If overweight or obese, aim for gradual weight loss through healthy eating and regular exercise to reduce the risk of heart disease.  Quit Smoking: If you smoke, quit smoking to reduce the risk of heart disease and other health complications. Seek support from healthcare professionals, smoking cessation programs, or support groups to help you quit smoking successfully.  Limit Alcohol Consumption: Drink alcohol in moderation, if at all. Limit alcohol intake to no more than one drink per day for women and up to two drinks per day for men. Excessive alcohol consumption can increase blood pressure, contribute to weight gain, and raise the risk of heart disease. Manage Stress: Practice stress-reduction techniques such as deep breathing, meditation, yoga, mindfulness, or progressive muscle relaxation to manage stress effectively. Chronic stress can contribute to high blood pressure, inflammation, and other risk factors for heart disease.  Monitor Blood Pressure: Monitor blood pressure regularly and work with a healthcare provider to maintain healthy blood pressure levels. Follow recommendations for lifestyle modifications and, if necessary, take medications as prescribed to control high blood pressure. Manage Diabetes: If you have diabetes, work with a healthcare provider to manage blood sugar levels effectively through lifestyle modifications, medication adherence, regular monitoring, and preventive care to reduce the risk of heart disease complications.','Cardiologist','747384e6-199e-4ff0-b0a6-b0986292a1dd','2024-03-28 05:40:40','2024-03-28 05:40:40'),('Cervical spondylosis','Cervical spondylosis is a term that encompasses a wide range of progressive degenerative changes that affect all the components of the cervical spine. Cervical spondylosis is a natural age-related disease process that is associated with degenerative changes within the intervertebral disc. It most commonly presents as neck pain, which remains as one of the leading causes of disability. The primary risk factor and contributor to the incidence of cervical spondylosis is age-related degeneration of the intervertebral disc and cervical spinal elements. Degenerative changes in surrounding structures, including the uncovertebral joints, facets joints, posterior longitudinal ligament (PLL), and ligamentum flavum all combine to cause narrowing of the spinal canal and intervertebral foramina. Consequently, the spinal cord, spinal vasculature, and nerve roots can be compressed, resulting in the three clinical syndromes in which cervical spondylosis presents: axial neck pain, cervical myelopathy, and cervical radiculopathy.','Maintain Good Posture: Practice proper posture to reduce strain on your neck. Sit and stand with your shoulders back, chin tucked in, and spine aligned. Avoid slouching or hunching over, especially when using electronic devices or sitting for long periods.  Use Ergonomic Support: Use ergonomic furniture and accessories to support your neck and spine. Invest in a supportive chair with good lumbar support, and use a headset or speakerphone for extended phone conversations to avoid cradling the phone between your ear and shoulder.  Take Regular Breaks: If you have a desk job or spend long periods sitting, take frequent breaks to stretch and move around. Incorporate neck stretches and gentle range-of-motion exercises into your routine to alleviate stiffness and improve flexibility.  Avoid Heavy Lifting: Minimize lifting heavy objects, especially overhead or with poor lifting technique. Use proper lifting mechanics, such as bending at the knees and keeping your back straight, to reduce strain on your neck and spine. Stay Active: Stay physically active with low-impact exercises that promote neck strength, flexibility, and overall fitness. Activities such as walking, swimming, or cycling can help improve circulation, reduce inflammation, and alleviate symptoms.  Seek Professional Guidance: Consult with your healthcare provider or physical therapist for personalized advice on managing cervical spondylosis','Rheumatologist','7727511c-dfe8-4466-87e8-a8863c3a0682','2024-03-28 05:40:38','2024-03-28 05:40:38'),('(vertigo) Paroymsal  Positional Vertigo','Vertigo is a common presenting complaint in primary care and emergency departments. It is a symptom of vestibular dysfunction and has been described as a sensation of motion, most commonly rotational motion. Vertigo is a sensation of feeling off-balance, dizzy, or like the world is spinning around you when it\'s not. It\'s not a disease by itself, but rather a symptom of various conditions. One common cause is a problem in the inner ear, where balance is regulated','Precautions for vertigo depend on the underlying cause and individual circumstances. However, here are some general precautions that may help manage vertigo:      Avoid sudden movements: Abrupt head movements can trigger or worsen vertigo. Move slowly and cautiously, especially when getting up from lying down or changing positions.      Use handrails and support: When navigating stairs or walking in unstable environments, use handrails or grab onto stable objects to prevent falls.      Stay hydrated: Dehydration can exacerbate symptoms of vertigo. Drink plenty of water throughout the day.      Get adequate rest: Fatigue can worsen vertigo symptoms. Ensure you get enough sleep and rest when needed.      Avoid triggers: Identify and avoid factors that exacerbate vertigo symptoms, such as certain foods, stress, or environmental triggers like bright lights or loud noises.      Modify your environment: Make changes in your surroundings to minimize the risk of falls or accidents. Remove tripping hazards and ensure good lighting.      Consider physical therapy: Certain exercises and maneuvers prescribed by a physical therapist or healthcare provider may help alleviate symptoms and improve balance.      Medication adherence: If prescribed medication to manage vertigo or underlying conditions, take them as directed by your healthcare provider.      Stay informed: Learn about your condition and how to manage it effectively. Stay in communication with your healthcare provider to ensure you\'re receiving appropriate care.      Seek help when needed: If you experience severe or prolonged vertigo episodes, or if your symptoms worsen despite precautions, seek medical attention promptly.','ENT Specialist','78967b79-6fa0-4432-a957-0f7fc9918e0a','2024-03-28 05:40:37','2024-03-28 05:40:37'),('Urinary tract infection','A urinary tract infection (UTI) is a bacterial infection that affects any part of the urinary system, including the kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra. UTIs usually occur when bacteria, typically Escherichia coli (E. coli) from the digestive tract, enter the urinary tract through the urethra and begin to multiply. UTIs can also be caused by other bacteria, fungi, or viruses. Common symptoms of a UTI include a strong, persistent urge to urinate, a burning sensation during urination, passing frequent, small amounts of urine, cloudy or strong-smelling urine, pelvic pain (in women), and rectal pain (in men). Some individuals may also experience fever, chills, nausea, or back pain if the infection has spread to the kidneys. Diagnosis of a UTI typically involves a medical history, physical examination, and laboratory tests, such as urinalysis and urine culture. Urinalysis can detect the presence of white blood cells, red blood cells, and bacteria in the urine, while urine culture can identify the specific type of bacteria causing the infection and determine the most appropriate antibiotic treatment.  UTIs are usually treated with antibiotics to kill the bacteria causing the infection. The choice of antibiotic depends on the type of bacteria identified in the urine culture and the severity of the infection. Commonly prescribed antibiotics for UTIs include trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, nitrofurantoin, ciprofloxacin, and amoxicillin-clavulanate. It\'s important to complete the full course of antibiotics as prescribed by a healthcare provider to ensure effective treatment and prevent recurrence of the infection. If left untreated, UTIs can lead to more serious complications, such as kidney infections (pyelonephritis), bloodstream infections (sepsis), and recurrent UTIs. Pregnant women, individuals with underlying health conditions (such as diabetes or kidney stones), and older adults may be at higher risk of developing complications from UTIs. Certain populations, such as pregnant women, individuals with recurrent UTIs, and those with structural abnormalities of the urinary tract, may require special considerations in the diagnosis and management of UTIs. Pregnant women, for example, may need to undergo urine testing at prenatal visits to screen for asymptomatic bacteriuria, which, if left untreated, can increase the risk of complications during pregnancy.','Stay Hydrated: Drink plenty of water throughout the day to help flush bacteria out of the urinary tract. Aim for at least eight glasses of water daily, unless otherwise advised by a healthcare provider. Empty Bladder Regularly: Urinate frequently and completely to prevent the buildup of bacteria in the urinary tract. Avoid holding urine for prolonged periods, as this can increase the risk of bacterial growth and UTIs. Practice Good Hygiene: Maintain good genital hygiene by wiping from front to back after using the restroom to prevent the spread of bacteria from the anal area to the urethra. Avoid using harsh soaps, douches, or feminine hygiene sprays, as these can irritate the genital area and disrupt the natural balance of bacteria. Maintain a Healthy Diet: Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins to support overall health and immune function. Certain foods and beverages, such as cranberry juice or supplements, may have properties that can help prevent UTIs, although more research is needed to confirm their effectiveness. Manage Chronic Conditions: If you have underlying health conditions such as diabetes or kidney stones that increase the risk of UTIs, work with your healthcare provider to manage these conditions effectively and reduce the risk of recurrent infections','PCP','807a172b-a197-45cd-826d-6f1a27a3d3ee','2024-03-28 05:40:44','2024-03-28 05:40:44'),('Peptic ulcer diseae','Peptic ulcer disease refers to painful sores or ulcers that develop on the lining of the stomach, small intestine, or esophagus.  Peptic ulcers occur when the protective lining of the stomach or small intestine becomes damaged, allowing stomach acid and digestive juices to irritate and erode the underlying tissues. This can lead to the formation of open sores or ulcers. Peptic ulcers are often caused by infection with Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori) bacteria, long-term use of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) such as aspirin or ibuprofen, excessive alcohol consumption, smoking, and certain medical conditions like Zollinger-Ellison syndrome. Common symptoms of peptic ulcers include abdominal pain or discomfort, which may be described as burning, gnawing, or dull, particularly between meals or at night. Other symptoms may include bloating, belching, nausea, vomiting, and unintended weight loss. Diagnosis of peptic ulcer disease typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and diagnostic tests such as upper gastrointestinal endoscopy (EGD), where a flexible tube with a camera is inserted into the throat to visualize the stomach and small intestine. Blood tests, stool tests, or breath tests may also be performed to detect H. pylori infection. If left untreated, peptic ulcers can lead to serious complications such as internal bleeding, perforation (a hole in the stomach or intestine wall), or obstruction (blockage) of the digestive tract. These complications may require urgent medical attention and intervention, including hospitalization and surgery.','Medication Adherence: Take prescribed medications, such as proton pump inhibitors (PPIs), H2-receptor antagonists, and antibiotics for H. pylori eradication, exactly as directed by your healthcare provider. Skipping doses or stopping medications prematurely can increase the risk of ulcer recurrence. Avoid NSAIDs: Minimize or avoid the use of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) such as aspirin, ibuprofen, and naproxen, as they can irritate the stomach lining and contribute to ulcer formation or exacerbation. If necessary, discuss alternative pain management strategies with your healthcare provider. Limit Alcohol Consumption: Excessive alcohol consumption can increase stomach acid production and irritate the stomach lining, potentially worsening peptic ulcer symptoms. Limit alcohol intake to moderate levels or avoid it altogether to reduce the risk of ulcer complications. Quit Smoking: Smoking can impair the healing of peptic ulcers and increase the risk of ulcer recurrence. Quitting smoking can improve ulcer healing, reduce symptoms, and lower the risk of complications associated with peptic ulcer disease. Stress Management: Chronic stress can exacerbate peptic ulcer symptoms and delay healing. Practice stress-reduction techniques such as deep breathing, meditation, yoga, or engaging in relaxing activities to help manage stress and promote ulcer healing. Limit Caffeine and Carbonated Beverages: Caffeinated and carbonated beverages can stimulate stomach acid production and exacerbate peptic ulcer symptoms. Limit intake of coffee, tea, soda, and other caffeinated or carbonated drinks to reduce irritation of the stomach lining. Maintain a Healthy Weight: Obesity and excess abdominal fat can increase the risk of developing peptic ulcers and worsen symptoms. Maintain a healthy weight through regular exercise and a balanced diet to reduce the risk of ulcer complications.','Gastroenterologist','81646071-5781-45a5-93cd-50a7029e89b4','2024-03-28 05:40:43','2024-03-28 05:40:43'),('Arthritis','Arthritis is defined as an acute or chronic joint inflammation in the joint. Arthritis may attribute to a wide variety of symptoms that include pain, stiffness, decreased range of motion, and joint deformities. There are several different types of arthritis, with management being different for each. History and physical examination are crucial in recognizing the type of arthritis, while additional laboratory and imaging may sometimes be necessary for confirming the diagnosis.','Maintain a Healthy Weight: Excess weight can put added stress on your joints, particularly weight-bearing joints like the knees and hips. Maintaining a healthy weight can help reduce strain on your joints and alleviate arthritis symptoms.  Stay Active: Regular exercise can help improve joint flexibility, strengthen muscles around the joints, and reduce pain and stiffness. Low-impact activities like walking, swimming, cycling, and gentle stretching exercises are often beneficial for people with arthritis.  Use Joint Protection Techniques: When performing activities that involve repetitive motions or strain on the joints, use joint protection techniques to reduce stress. This may include using assistive devices like braces, splints, or ergonomic tools, as well as practicing proper body mechanics and avoiding overuse of affected joints. Follow a Balanced Diet: Eating a nutritious, balanced diet can help support joint health and reduce inflammation. Include plenty of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats in your diet, and limit processed foods, sugary snacks, and foods high in saturated fats.  Stay Hydrated: Drinking an adequate amount of water is essential for maintaining joint health and supporting overall bodily functions. Aim to drink plenty of water throughout the day to stay hydrated and keep your joints lubricated.  Consult Healthcare Providers: Work closely with your healthcare team, including your primary care physician, rheumatologist, physical therapist, and other specialists, to develop a personalized arthritis management plan tailored to your specific needs and circumstances.','Rheumatologist','87ca72d6-dede-4745-9616-68680018433a','2024-03-28 05:40:38','2024-03-28 05:40:38'),('Chronic cholestasis','Vanishing bile duct syndrome (VBDS) is a rare but serious outcome and complication of drug induced liver injury marked clinically by chronic cholestasis and histologically by loss of intrahepatic bile ducts. VBDS typically occurs after a bout of severe cholestatic hepatitis, often with immunoallergic features. Furthermore, there are great variations in severity and outcome of VBDS. Most cases of VBDS arise within a few months of onset of severe cholestatic hepatitis, often with immunoallergic features such as rash, fever, facial edema, lymphadenopathy and eosinophilia; and in more dramatic cases with Stevens Johnson syndrome or toxic epidermal necrolysis. VBDS can be relentless and progressive, with almost complete loss of bile ducts accompanied by severe cholestasis and hepatic failure leading to death or need for liver transplantation within 1 to 3 years of onset','Follow Treatment Plan: Adhere to the treatment plan prescribed by your healthcare provider. This may include taking medications as directed, following dietary recommendations, and attending regular follow-up appointments.  Maintain a Healthy Diet: Eat a well-balanced diet that is low in saturated fats and cholesterol to reduce the burden on the liver. Include plenty of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats in your diet. Limit processed foods, sugary beverages, and alcohol consumption.  Stay Hydrated: Drink plenty of water throughout the day to stay hydrated and support liver function. Aim for at least 8-10 glasses of water daily, or more if recommended by your healthcare provider.  Avoid Alcohol and Tobacco: Alcohol and tobacco can further damage the liver and worsen symptoms of chronic cholestasis. Avoid or limit alcohol consumption, and if you smoke, consider quitting to reduce the risk of complications.  Practice Good Hygiene: Wash your hands frequently with soap and water, especially before handling food or eating, to reduce the risk of infections. Avoid close contact with individuals who have contagious illnesses to minimize the risk of secondary infections.  Manage Itching: If you experience itching (pruritus) as a symptom of chronic cholestasis, take steps to manage it effectively. Use fragrance-free moisturizers to keep your skin hydrated, wear loose-fitting clothing made of natural fibers, and avoid hot baths or showers that can exacerbate itching. Discuss with your healthcare provider about medications or topical treatments that may help alleviate itching. Monitor Symptoms: Keep track of your symptoms and any changes in your health. Report any new or worsening symptoms to your healthcare provider promptly, as early intervention can help prevent complications and improve outcomes.','Hepatologist','9aed2617-43d4-45c2-b1c2-868791b9768c','2024-03-28 05:40:38','2024-03-28 05:40:38'),('Malaria','Malaria is a serious and sometimes life-threatening disease caused by the bite of an infected mosquito. Malaria is caused by parasites of the Plasmodium species, which are transmitted to humans through the bite of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. When an infected mosquito bites a person, the malaria parasites enter the bloodstream and travel to the liver, where they multiply and mature. They then re-enter the bloodstream and infect red blood cells, leading to symptoms of malaria. Symptoms of malaria can include fever, chills, sweats, headache, body aches, fatigue, nausea, and vomiting. In severe cases, malaria can cause complications such as organ failure, severe anemia, or cerebral malaria (a serious neurological complication). Malaria is diagnosed through blood tests that detect the presence of malaria parasites in the bloodstream. Rapid diagnostic tests (RDTs) are commonly used in areas where microscopy is not readily available. Malaria is a major public health concern, particularly in tropical and subtropical regions of the world. It disproportionately affects children under five years of age and pregnant women, contributing to significant morbidity and mortality worldwide.','If you develop symptoms of malaria, such as fever, chills, headache, or body aches, seek prompt medical attention for diagnosis and treatment. Early diagnosis and treatment are essential to prevent complications and reduce the risk of transmission to others. Pregnant women should take extra precautions to prevent malaria, as they are at increased risk of severe complications. Consult with a healthcare provider for appropriate preventive measures and treatment options during pregnancy. Sleep under insecticide-treated bed nets, especially in areas where malaria is prevalent, to reduce the risk of mosquito bites while sleeping. Apply insect repellents containing DEET, picaridin, or other recommended ingredients to exposed skin and clothing to repel mosquitoes. Take steps to reduce mosquito breeding sites around homes and communities by emptying standing water from containers, covering water storage containers, and maintaining clean surroundings.','PCP','a2ce2115-4eae-4295-839d-8bdb7c3f611a','2024-03-28 05:40:42','2024-03-28 05:40:42'),('Jaundice','','','','a89bb6e5-75e1-4475-bbf3-a9574bbc2d9a','2024-03-28 05:40:42','2024-03-28 05:40:42'),('Bronchial Asthma','Asthma is a common disease and has a range of severity, from a very mild, occasional wheeze to acute, life-threatening airway closure. It usually presents in childhood and is associated with other features of atopy, such as eczema and hayfever. Asthma is a chronic disease of the air passages characterized by inflammation and narrowing of the airways. Symptoms of asthma include shortness of breath, cough, and wheezing. It happens when the airways in your lungs, called bronchial tubes, become swollen and inflamed. This makes it hard for air to flow in and out of your lungs','Precautions for managing bronchial asthma focus on preventing symptoms, reducing the frequency of asthma attacks, and improving overall lung health.  Identify and Avoid Triggers: Learn about your asthma triggers and take steps to avoid or minimize exposure to them. Common triggers include allergens (such as pollen, dust mites, mold, and pet dander), irritants (like smoke, pollution, strong odors, and cold air), respiratory infections, exercise, and stress.  Take Medications as Prescribed: Use asthma medications as prescribed by your healthcare provider. This may include quick-relief medications (rescue inhalers) to relieve acute symptoms and long-term control medications (inhaled corticosteroids, long-acting beta agonists, leukotriene modifiers, etc.) to manage inflammation and prevent asthma attacks. Stay Active: Engage in regular physical activity to improve lung function and overall fitness. Choose activities that are suitable for your asthma severity and fitness level, and use preventive measures','Pulmonologist','b1a95ee6-4534-4863-aba7-75e5d9baa634','2024-03-28 05:40:38','2024-03-28 05:40:38'),('Hypothyroidism','Hypothyroidism is a condition where the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormone, leading to a slowdown in bodily functions. The thyroid gland, located in the neck, produces hormones that regulate metabolism, energy levels, and other bodily functions. These hormones include thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3). Hypothyroidism occurs when the thyroid gland becomes underactive and produces insufficient thyroid hormones. This can happen due to various reasons, such as autoimmune diseases like Hashimoto\'s thyroiditis, thyroid surgery, radiation therapy, certain medications, iodine deficiency, or congenital factors. Symptoms of hypothyroidism can include fatigue, weight gain, sensitivity to cold, constipation, dry skin, hair loss, muscle weakness, joint pain, depression, memory problems, and menstrual irregularities in women. Untreated or poorly managed hypothyroidism can lead to complications such as goiter (enlarged thyroid gland), cardiovascular problems, infertility, birth defects in pregnant women, and myxedema coma (a rare but life-threatening condition characterized by severe hypothyroidism). In addition to medication, lifestyle modifications such as eating a balanced diet, getting regular exercise, managing stress, and avoiding excessive iodine intake can help support thyroid function and overall health. Hypothyroidism is usually a lifelong condition that requires ongoing management with medication. It\'s essential for patients to take their medication as prescribed, attend regular follow-up appointments, and communicate any concerns or changes in symptoms to their healthcare provider.','Manage Stress: Chronic stress can affect thyroid function and exacerbate symptoms of hypothyroidism. Practice stress-reduction techniques such as mindfulness, meditation, deep breathing exercises, yoga, or engaging in hobbies and activities you enjoy. Maintain a Balanced Diet: Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, and whole grains to support overall health and thyroid function. Include sources of iodine such as seafood, dairy products, and iodized salt in moderation, but don\'t rely solely on iodine for thyroid health. Avoid Excessive Iodine Intake: While iodine is essential for thyroid hormone production, excessive iodine intake can be harmful, especially for individuals with hypothyroidism. Avoid consuming large amounts of iodine-rich foods or supplements unless specifically advised by a healthcare provider. Get Adequate Sleep: Prioritize getting enough sleep each night to support overall health and well-being. Aim for 7-9 hours of quality sleep per night to help regulate hormones and support thyroid function. Avoid Tobacco: If you smoke, consider quitting. Smoking can interfere with thyroid function and worsen symptoms of hypothyroidism. Seek support and resources to quit smoking if needed. Stay Hydrated: Drink plenty of water throughout the day to support hydration and overall health. Adequate hydration is important for proper thyroid function and can help alleviate symptoms such as fatigue and constipation.','Endocrinologists','b7526d7e-b107-4df8-8c9b-d9e1f8e666c2','2024-03-28 05:40:42','2024-03-28 05:40:42'),('Acne','Acne vulgaris is a common cutaneous inflammatory disorder (also known as skin inflammation, a genral term to describe skin irritation or swelling), of the hair follicle, hair shaft and sebaceous gland (the Pilosebaceous Unit). The condition commonly manifests with papules, pustules, or nodules primarily on the face, although it can also affect the upper arms, trunk, and back. The pathogenesis of acne vulgaris involves the interaction of multiple factors that ultimately lead to the formation of its primary lesion, which is known as \"comedo\", Acne can appear in diffrent forms:     Blackheads: Open pores with dark spots.     Whiteheads: Closed pores with small white bumps.     Pimples: Red bumps filled with pus.     Cysts and nodules: Larger, deeper lumps under the skin.','Regular cleansing with a gentle cleanser and avoiding harsh scrubbing can help prevent acne. Also, avoiding oil-based skincare products and cosmetics can reduce the risk of pore blockage. Additionally, maintaining a healthy lifestyle with a balanced diet and managing stress can contribute to clearer skin.','Dermatologist','bafeac1f-866e-4713-9020-783d3fdd6377','2024-03-28 05:40:37','2024-03-28 05:40:37'),('Alcoholic hepatitis','Alcoholic hepatitis is a severe syndrome related to alcoholic liver disease. It is characterized by rapid onset of jaundice, malaise, tender hepatomegaly, and subtle features of systemic inflammatory response. Alcoholic hepatitis usually progresses to cirrhosis if drinking is continued. For those who discontinue alcohol, hepatitis returns to normal within a few months but the cirrhosis that has already occurred does not reverse. Although the amount of alcohol ingested is the most important risk factor for the development of chronic liver disease, the progression to alcohol-induced chronic liver disease is neither dose-dependent nor is the correlation with the quantity of alcohol consumed and liver injury linear. Even shorter durations of alcohol abuse could lead to AH. A typical patient would be between 40 to 60 years of age with a history of more than 100 g/day of alcohol consumption for a decade, in whom you have ruled out other causes of acute hepatitis ','The best way to prevent alcoholic hepatitis is to limit alcohol consumption and avoid excessive drinking. If you\'re struggling to control your alcohol intake, seeking help from a healthcare provider or support group can be beneficial.','Hepatologist','c190e9cf-47e0-414f-bb42-4ef4f6c5cbf1','2024-03-28 05:40:38','2024-03-28 05:40:38'),('AIDS','AIDS stands for Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome. It\'s a serious condition caused by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV). HIV weakens the body\'s immune system, making it harder for the body to fight off infections and diseases. This disease can\'t be dignosis from the symptoms only you should consult your healthcare provider befor making any further steps. When someone has AIDS, their immune system is severely damaged, leaving them vulnerable to a wide range of infections and illnesses that a healthy immune system would normally fight off easily. These infections, called opportunistic infections, can be life-threatening.Human immunodeficiency virus is transmitted sexually, via blood transfusions, sharing intravenous needles, and from the mother to a child during the birth process and breastfeeding. Most patients diagnosed with HIV will develop AIDS within ten years if left untreated. With the initiation of antiretroviral therapy after AIDS diagnosis, the patient may live for greater than ten years and even have a normal life span. Once a patient has been diagnosed with AIDS and they do not receive ART, they will probably die within two years.','Seek Support: If you\'re living with HIV/AIDS or are at risk, seek support from healthcare providers, counselors, or support groups. Emotional support can be as important as medical treatment in managing HIV/AIDS. Educate Yourself: Learn more about HIV/AIDS transmission and prevention strategies to make informed decisions about your health. Use Sterile Equipment: If you\'re getting a tattoo, piercing, or medical procedure involving needles, ensure that sterile equipment is used to prevent the risk of HIV transmission. Get Tested Regularly: Knowing your HIV status is crucial for your health and for preventing the spread of the virus. Get tested regularly, especially if you engage in high-risk behaviors or have a new sexual partner.','PCP','cadb1cca-fe4a-465d-9796-9adfd935cc34','2024-03-28 05:40:37','2024-03-28 05:40:37'),('Diabetes ','Diabetes mellitus (DM) is a metabolic disease, involving inappropriately elevated blood glucose levels (how your body uses glucose (sugar), which is the main source of energy for your cells), DM has several categories, including type 1, type 2, maturity-onset diabetes of the young (MODY), gestational diabetes, neonatal diabetes, and secondary causes due to endocrinopathies, steroid use, etc. The main subtypes of DM are Type 1 diabetes mellitus (T1DM) and Type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM), which classically result from defective insulin secretion (T1DM) and/or action (T2DM). T1DM presents in children or adolescents, while T2DM is thought to affect middle-aged and older adults who have prolonged hyperglycemia due to poor lifestyle and dietary choices. A patient with DM has the potential for hyperglycemia. The pathology of DM can be unclear since several factors can often contribute to the disease. Hyperglycemia alone can impair pancreatic beta-cell function and contributes to impaired insulin secretion. Consequentially, there is a vicious cycle of hyperglycemia leading to an impaired metabolic state. Overall, diabetes is a manageable condition with proper treatment, lifestyle modifications, and ongoing support. With good management, people with diabetes can lead healthy, active lives and reduce their risk of complications','Monitor Blood Sugar Levels: Check your blood sugar levels regularly as advised by your healthcare provider. Monitoring helps you understand how food, physical activity, medications, and other factors affect your blood sugar levels, allowing you to make informed decisions about your diabetes management.  Follow a Healthy Diet: Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. Limit your intake of processed foods, sugary beverages, refined carbohydrates, and foods high in saturated and trans fats. Portion control and meal timing are also important for managing blood sugar levels.  Stay Active: Engage in regular physical activity to help control blood sugar levels, improve insulin sensitivity, and maintain a healthy weight. Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic activity or 75 minutes of vigorous-intensity activity each week, as recommended by guidelines. Manage Stress: Stress can affect blood sugar levels and overall health. Practice stress-reduction techniques such as deep breathing, meditation, yoga, or hobbies that you enjoy. Adequate sleep and relaxation are also important for managing stress.','PCP','d35c84ea-31bb-4842-ad3a-b2768bc18298','2024-03-28 05:40:39','2024-03-28 05:40:39'),('Chicken pox','Chickenpox or varicella is a contagious disease caused by the varicella-zoster virus (VZV). The virus is responsible for chickenpox (usually primary infection in non-immune hosts) and herpes zoster or shingles (following reactivation of latent infection). Chickenpox results in a skin rash that forms small, itchy blisters, which scabs over. It typically starts on the chest, back, and face then spreads. It is accompanied by fever, fatigue, pharyngitis, and headaches which usually last five to seven days. Chickenpox is a worldwide, airborne disease that is spread by coughing and sneezing, and also by contact with skin lesions. It may start to spread one to two days before the rash appears until all lesions are crusted over. Patients with shingles may spread chickenpox to those who are not immune through blister contact. The disease is diagnosed based on the presenting symptoms and confirmed by polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing of the blister fluid or scabs Overall, chickenpox is a common childhood illness that usually resolves on its own without serious complications.','Avoid Close Contact: If you or someone in your household has chickenpox, avoid close contact with others, especially those who haven\'t had chickenpox before or haven\'t been vaccinated against it. Stay home from work, school, or other public places until all the chickenpox blisters have crusted over.  Cover Mouth and Nose: Cover your mouth and nose with a tissue or your elbow when coughing or sneezing to prevent the spread of respiratory droplets containing the virus. Dispose of used tissues properly and wash your hands thoroughly afterward.  Practice Good Hygiene: Wash your hands frequently with soap and water, especially after coughing, sneezing, or caring for someone with chickenpox. Proper hand hygiene can help prevent the spread of the virus to yourself and others.  Keep Fingernails Short: Trim your fingernails short to reduce the risk of scratching the chickenpox blisters and spreading the virus to other parts of your body or to others.  Avoid Scratching: Although it can be tempting, avoid scratching the chickenpox blisters to prevent bacterial infection and scarring. Keep the skin clean and dry, and use calamine lotion or oatmeal baths to soothe itching. Vaccination: The best way to prevent chickenpox is through vaccination. The chickenpox vaccine is safe and effective and is routinely recommended for children as part of their immunization schedule. Vaccination not only protects individuals from getting chickenpox but also helps prevent the spread of the virus to others.','Dermatologist','d3b1f4bb-e897-4e33-a7ac-b260e27fb4de','2024-03-28 05:40:38','2024-03-28 05:40:38'),('GERD','Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease, is a chronic digestive disorder where stomach acid flows back into the esophagus, causing irritation and inflammation, Normally, a muscular ring called the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) closes after food passes into the stomach. In GERD, the LES doesn\'t close properly, allowing stomach acid and sometimes partially digested food to reflux (backflow) into the esophagus.  Common symptoms of GERD include heartburn (a burning sensation in the chest), regurgitation (acidic taste in the mouth), chest pain, difficulty swallowing, chronic cough, hoarseness, and a sensation of a lump in the throat. Several factors can contribute to GERD, including a weak LES, hiatal hernia (when part of the stomach pushes up through the diaphragm into the chest), obesity, pregnancy, smoking, certain medications, and certain foods and drinks. If left untreated, GERD can lead to complications such as esophagitis (inflammation of the esophagus), esophageal ulcers, Barrett\'s esophagus (a precancerous condition), strictures (narrowing of the esophagus), and an increased risk of esophageal cancer.','Dietary Modifications: Avoid foods and beverages that can trigger acid reflux, such as spicy or acidic foods, fatty foods, caffeine, chocolate, peppermint, citrus fruits and juices, alcohol, and carbonated drinks. Opt for smaller, more frequent meals instead of large, heavy meals.  Weight Management: Maintain a healthy weight to reduce pressure on the abdomen and lower esophageal sphincter (LES), which can help prevent acid reflux. If overweight or obese, aim to achieve gradual weight loss through a balanced diet and regular exercise.  Eating Habits: Eat slowly and chew food thoroughly to aid digestion. Avoid lying down or bending over immediately after eating, as this can increase the risk of acid reflux. Wait at least two to three hours before lying down or going to bed.  Posture: Elevate the head of the bed by raising the mattress or using bed risers to create a slight incline. This can help prevent stomach acid from refluxing into the esophagus while sleeping. Avoid lying completely flat, as this can exacerbate symptoms.  Clothing: Avoid wearing tight-fitting clothing, especially around the abdomen, as it can increase pressure on the stomach and LES, leading to acid reflux.  Smoking Cessation: If you smoke, quit smoking to reduce the risk of acid reflux and other complications associated with GERD. Smoking can weaken the LES and increase stomach acid production.  Stress Management: Practice stress-reduction techniques such as deep breathing, meditation, yoga, or tai chi to help manage stress, which can exacerbate GERD symptoms. Adequate stress management can help prevent flare-ups of acid reflux. Avoid Late-Night Snacking: Avoid eating large meals or heavy snacks late at night, especially close to bedtime. Allow sufficient time for digestion before lying down to sleep to reduce the risk of acid reflux during the night.  Hydration: Stay hydrated by drinking plenty of water throughout the day. However, avoid drinking large amounts of water with meals, as this can dilute stomach acid and impair digestion, potentially exacerbating GERD symptoms.','Gastroenterologist','d5eff461-3807-4a5e-afec-3c3d84f95c26','2024-03-28 05:40:40','2024-03-28 05:40:40'),('Migraine','Migraine is a neurological condition characterized by recurrent, intense headaches often accompanied by other symptoms. Migraine headaches are usually moderate to severe in intensity and can last for hours to days. They often occur on one side of the head and are described as pulsating or throbbing. The pain can be debilitating and may worsen with physical activity. Migraine attacks can be triggered by various factors, which vary from person to person. Common triggers include certain foods (such as aged cheese, chocolate, and processed meats), hormonal changes (such as fluctuations in estrogen levels), stress, lack of sleep, dehydration, bright lights, strong smells, and changes in weather. The exact cause of migraines is not fully understood, but they are believed to involve a combination of genetic, environmental, and neurological factors. Changes in brain chemistry and abnormal activation of certain brain areas are thought to play a role in migraine attacks. There are several types of migraines, including migraine with aura (where aura symptoms precede the headache), migraine without aura, vestibular migraine (accompanied by dizziness or vertigo), and menstrual migraine (associated with the menstrual cycle). In addition to headache pain, migraines may be accompanied by other symptoms, such as nausea, vomiting, sensitivity to light (photophobia), and sensitivity to sound (phonophobia). Some people may also experience visual disturbances called aura, which can include flashing lights, zigzag lines, or blind spots. Lifestyle changes can help manage migraines and reduce the frequency of attacks. Strategies may include identifying and avoiding triggers, maintaining a regular sleep schedule, staying hydrated, practicing stress-reduction techniques (such as relaxation exercises or meditation), and adopting a healthy diet.','Identify Triggers: Keep a migraine diary to track potential triggers such as foods, stressors, hormonal changes, sleep patterns, and environmental factors. Once identified, try to avoid or minimize exposure to triggers whenever possible. Manage Stress: Practice stress management techniques such as relaxation exercises, deep breathing, meditation, yoga, or progressive muscle relaxation. Stress is a common trigger for migraines, so finding healthy ways to cope with stress can help reduce the frequency of attacks. Limit Screen Time: Reduce exposure to screens, such as computers, smartphones, and television, as excessive screen time can strain the eyes and trigger migraines, especially in individuals prone to visual triggers. Limit Caffeine and Alcohol: Limit consumption of caffeine and alcoholic beverages, as these substances can trigger migraines in some individuals. Be mindful of your intake and consider reducing or eliminating these triggers if they worsen your symptoms. Healthy Diet: Maintain a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins. Avoid skipping meals or fasting for prolonged periods, as low blood sugar levels can trigger migraines in some individuals. If you experience frequent or severe migraines despite taking preventive measures, consult with your healthcare provider for further evaluation and treatment options. Your healthcare provider can help identify additional strategies to manage your migraines effectively.','Neurologist','d97a6b1c-1b82-4d78-bee0-042cad9faf54','2024-03-28 05:40:42','2024-03-28 05:40:42'),('Hepatitis C','Hepatitis C is a viral infection that affects the liver, Hepatitis C is caused by the hepatitis C virus (HCV), which is transmitted through contact with infected blood. It can be spread through sharing needles or syringes, receiving contaminated blood transfusions or organ transplants, needlestick injuries in healthcare settings, or from mother to baby during childbirth. Hepatitis C infection can be acute, meaning it is a short-term illness that occurs within the first six months after exposure to the virus. Most people with acute hepatitis C do not have symptoms or have mild symptoms. However, if left untreated, acute hepatitis C can progress to a chronic infection, which can lead to long-term liver damage, cirrhosis (scarring of the liver), liver failure, or liver cancer. Many people with hepatitis C infection do not have symptoms, especially in the early stages of the disease. However, some individuals may experience symptoms such as fatigue, jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes), dark urine, abdominal pain, loss of appetite, nausea, or joint pain. Chronic hepatitis C infection may not cause symptoms for many years but can lead to serious liver complications if left untreated. Hepatitis C infection is diagnosed through blood tests that detect the presence of HCV antibodies and HCV RNA (viral load). These tests can determine whether the infection is acute or chronic and assess the severity of liver damage. People with chronic hepatitis C infection require regular monitoring by a healthcare provider to assess liver function, monitor viral load, and screen for liver-related complications such as cirrhosis or liver cancer. Lifestyle modifications, such as avoiding alcohol and maintaining a healthy diet, may also be recommended to support liver health. Unlike hepatitis B, there is currently no vaccine available to prevent hepatitis C infection. However, efforts to prevent transmission through safe injection practices, blood screening, and harm reduction strategies can help reduce the spread of the virus.','Practice Good Hygiene: Wash your hands thoroughly with soap and water after using the bathroom, changing diapers, or coming into contact with blood or bodily fluids. Proper hand hygiene can help prevent the spread of hepatitis C and other infectious diseases. Use Personal Protective Equipment: Healthcare workers and others who may come into contact with blood or bodily fluids should use appropriate personal protective equipment (PPE), such as gloves, gowns, masks, and eye protection, to reduce the risk of exposure to hepatitis C and other infectious agents. Avoid Sharing Personal Items: Avoid sharing personal items that may come into contact with blood, such as razors, toothbrushes, nail clippers, or personal hygiene items. Hepatitis C virus can survive outside the body for extended periods, so it\'s essential to avoid sharing items that may carry the virus. Ensure Sterile Medical Procedures: Ensure that medical and dental equipment is properly sterilized and that healthcare settings follow strict infection control practices to prevent the transmission of hepatitis C and other bloodborne pathogens. If you undergo medical or dental procedures, ensure that sterile equipment is used to reduce the risk of infection. Consider Hepatitis C Testing: Individuals at increased risk of hepatitis C infection, such as current or former injection drug users, individuals with HIV infection, healthcare workers with occupational exposure, and individuals born to mothers with hepatitis C, should consider hepatitis C testing to identify infection early and access appropriate care and treatment if needed.','Hepatologist','f1ba8991-932f-4537-9c4f-cc6974b0d730','2024-03-28 05:40:41','2024-03-28 05:40:41'),('Dimorphic hemmorhoids(piles)','Hemorrhoids, also known as piles, are swollen veins in the lower rectum and anus. They can be internal (inside the rectum) or external (under the skin around the anus). Common symptoms of hemorrhoids include pain, itching, discomfort, swelling, and bleeding during bowel movements. Internal hemorrhoids may protrude through the anus (prolapse) or cause bleeding without pain. External hemorrhoids can cause pain and discomfort, especially during sitting or bowel movements.  Hemorrhoids can develop due to various factors, including straining during bowel movements, chronic constipation or diarrhea, sitting for long periods, obesity, pregnancy, and aging','Dietary Modifications: Eat a high-fiber diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and legumes. Fiber helps soften stools and promote regular bowel movements, reducing the strain on hemorrhoids during bowel movements. Drink plenty of water to stay hydrated, which also aids in digestion.  Avoid Straining: Straining during bowel movements can exacerbate hemorrhoid symptoms and lead to further irritation and swelling. Avoid constipation by not delaying bowel movements when you feel the urge, and avoid straining or pushing excessively during bowel movements.  Gentle Cleansing: Practice gentle hygiene after bowel movements to keep the anal area clean and prevent irritation. Use unscented, alcohol-free moist wipes or soft, unscented toilet paper to pat the area gently instead of wiping vigorously. Avoid harsh soaps or wipes that may further irritate the skin.  Warm Baths: Soaking in a warm bath (sitz bath) for about 10 to 15 minutes several times a day can help soothe hemorrhoid symptoms, reduce swelling, and promote healing. Adding Epsom salts or baking soda to the bathwater may provide additional relief. Avoid Sitting or Standing for Prolonged Periods: Prolonged sitting or standing can increase pressure on the veins in the rectum and worsen hemorrhoid symptoms. Take breaks to move around and avoid sitting on hard surfaces for long periods. Use cushions or pillows to provide support and relieve pressure on the anal area when sitting. Manage Chronic Diarrhea or Constipation: If you have chronic diarrhea or constipation, work with your healthcare provider to manage these conditions effectively. Medications, dietary changes, and lifestyle modifications may be recommended to help regulate bowel movements and reduce the risk of aggravating hemorrhoids.','Colorectal Surgeon','f373d927-9c65-4f21-9b0f-f22e29999417','2024-03-28 05:40:39','2024-03-28 05:40:39'),('Drug Reaction','Drug reactions, often referred to as adverse drug reactions (ADRs), occur when a medication causes an unwanted or harmful effect in a person\'s body.  Drug reactions can be classified into several types, including side effects, allergic reactions, drug interactions, and idiosyncratic reactions. Side effects are common and typically mild, while allergic reactions involve the body\'s immune system reacting to the medication. Drug interactions occur when two or more medications interact in the body, sometimes leading to unexpected effects. Idiosyncratic reactions are rare and unpredictable reactions that occur in a small percentage of people. Drug reactions can occur for various reasons, including individual differences in metabolism, genetic factors, underlying medical conditions, interactions with other medications or substances, and improper use of medications (such as incorrect dosage or duration of treatment).','Follow Prescribed Dosages: Take medications exactly as prescribed by your healthcare provider. Do not exceed the recommended dosage, and do not stop or change the dosage of a medication without consulting your healthcare provider.  Read Medication Labels: Read medication labels and patient information leaflets carefully before taking any medication. Pay attention to dosage instructions, potential side effects, and warnings.  Avoid Alcohol and Certain Foods: Some medications may interact with alcohol or specific foods, leading to adverse reactions or reduced effectiveness. Avoid consuming alcohol or foods that may interact with your medications unless approved by your healthcare provider.  Monitor for Side Effects: Be vigilant for any unusual symptoms or side effects while taking medications. Contact your healthcare provider if you experience any new or worsening symptoms, even if they seem minor.','PCP','f581b18d-8ee5-4ede-af9d-7162bd911ae9','2024-03-28 05:40:39','2024-03-28 05:40:39'),('Paralysis (brain hemorrhage)','A brain hemorrhage, also known as a cerebral hemorrhage or intracranial hemorrhage, occurs when there is bleeding in the brain tissue. A brain hemorrhage occurs when a blood vessel in the brain ruptures or leaks, causing blood to spill into the surrounding brain tissue. This can occur suddenly due to trauma, such as a head injury, or spontaneously due to conditions like high blood pressure, aneurysms, or certain medications. There are several types of brain hemorrhages, including intracerebral hemorrhage (bleeding directly into the brain tissue), subarachnoid hemorrhage (bleeding into the space between the brain and the surrounding membrane), and subdural or epidural hemorrhage (bleeding outside the brain but within the skull). Symptoms of a brain hemorrhage can vary depending on the location and severity of the bleeding but may include sudden and severe headache, nausea, vomiting, weakness or numbness on one side of the body, difficulty speaking or understanding speech, vision changes, confusion, loss of consciousness, and seizures. Several factors can increase the risk of a brain hemorrhage, including high blood pressure, advanced age, head trauma, certain medical conditions (such as arteriovenous malformations or blood clotting disorders), use of blood-thinning medications, smoking, and excessive alcohol consumption. Diagnosis of a brain hemorrhage typically involves a neurological examination, imaging tests such as a CT scan or MRI of the brain, and sometimes additional tests to evaluate the cause of the bleeding and assess its severity. While not all brain hemorrhages can be prevented, taking steps to manage high blood pressure, avoiding head injuries, and following a healthy lifestyle can help reduce the risk of certain types of brain hemorrhages.','Avoid Head Trauma: Minimize the risk of head injuries by wearing appropriate safety gear during sports and recreational activities, using seat belts while driving, and taking precautions to prevent falls, especially in older adults. Monitor Medications: Some medications, such as blood thinners (anticoagulants) or antiplatelet drugs, can increase the risk of bleeding and contribute to brain hemorrhage, especially when not used as prescribed or when combined with other medications. Follow healthcare provider instructions carefully and discuss any concerns about medication safety. Manage High Blood Pressure: High blood pressure (hypertension) is a significant risk factor for brain hemorrhage. Take steps to monitor and control blood pressure through lifestyle changes (such as maintaining a healthy diet, regular exercise, limiting sodium intake, reducing stress) and medications prescribed by a healthcare provider. Limit Alcohol Consumption: Excessive alcohol consumption can increase the risk of brain hemorrhage. Limit alcohol intake to moderate levels as recommended by healthcare providers (usually no more than one drink per day for women and two drinks per day for men). Quit Smoking: Smoking is associated with an increased risk of hypertension and vascular diseases that can contribute to brain hemorrhage. Quitting smoking can help reduce the risk of cardiovascular problems and promote overall health. Maintain a Healthy Lifestyle: Adopting a healthy lifestyle can help reduce the risk of vascular diseases and contribute to overall brain health. Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins, maintain a healthy weight, engage in regular physical activity, manage stress, and get an adequate amount of sleep each night.','Neurologist','f5ca7f1c-81d5-4869-be46-fadb834908aa','2024-03-28 05:40:42','2024-03-28 05:40:42'),('Hepatitis B','Hepatitis B is a viral infection that affects the liver. Viral Infection: Hepatitis B is caused by the hepatitis B virus (HBV), which is transmitted through contact with infected blood, semen, or other body fluids. It can be spread through unprotected sex, sharing needles or syringes, from mother to baby during childbirth, or through contact with blood or open sores of an infected person. Hepatitis B infection can be acute, meaning it is a short-term illness that occurs within the first six months after exposure to the virus. Most adults who get hepatitis B recover fully, but a small percentage develop a chronic infection, which can lead to long-term liver damage, cirrhosis (scarring of the liver), liver failure, or liver cancer. Some people with acute hepatitis B infection may have no symptoms, while others may experience symptoms such as fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, dark urine, clay-colored stools, joint pain, and jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes). Chronic hepatitis B infection may not cause symptoms for many years but can lead to serious liver complications if left untreated. The hepatitis B vaccine is highly effective in preventing hepatitis B infection. It is recommended for all infants at birth and for adults who are at increased risk of infection','Practice Good Hygiene: Wash your hands thoroughly with soap and water after using the bathroom, changing diapers, or coming into contact with blood or bodily fluids. Proper hand hygiene can help prevent the spread of hepatitis B and other infectious diseases. Avoid Sharing Personal Items: Avoid sharing personal items that may come into contact with blood or bodily fluids, such as razors, toothbrushes, nail clippers, or personal hygiene items. Hepatitis B virus can survive outside the body for extended periods, so it\'s essential to avoid sharing items that may carry the virus. Use Personal Protective Equipment: Healthcare workers and others who may come into contact with blood or bodily fluids should use appropriate personal protective equipment (PPE), such as gloves, gowns, masks, and eye protection, to reduce the risk of exposure to hepatitis B and other infectious agents. Ensure Sterile Medical Procedures: Ensure that medical and dental equipment is properly sterilized and that healthcare settings follow strict infection control practices to prevent the transmission of hepatitis B and other bloodborne pathogens. If you undergo medical or dental procedures, ensure that sterile equipment is used to reduce the risk of infection. Vaccination: The most effective way to prevent hepatitis B infection is through vaccination. Ensure that you and your family members receive the hepatitis B vaccine series, which is typically given as a three-dose series.','Hepatologist','f8d2aa6f-ddce-4293-b0e1-cf70c9fb8e69','2024-03-28 05:40:40','2024-03-28 05:40:40');
